\hypertarget{introduction}{%
\section{Introduction}\label{introduction}}

\begin{frame}{What is text analysis?}
\protect\hypertarget{what-is-text-analysis}{}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  As statisticians and data scientistis, why restrict ourselves to
  numeric data?
\item
  We can use text as data and employ statistical methods to derive
  patterns or trends

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Example: Given some song lyrics, can we determine who the singer is?
    What kinds of topics/sentiments does Lizzo like to sing about?
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[fragile]{Tidytext}
\protect\hypertarget{tidytext}{}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  So far in class, you have been employing tidy data principles, and we
  will continue to do so here!
\item
  Specifically, we will work in the `tidy text format': a table with one
  \textbf{token} per row
\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
## # A tibble: 11 x 3
##    text                                                  linenumber chapter
##    <chr>                                                      <int>   <int>
##  1 PRIDE AND PREJUDICE                                            1       0
##  2 ""                                                             2       0
##  3 By Jane Austen                                                 3       0
##  4 ""                                                             4       0
##  5 ""                                                             5       0
##  6 ""                                                             6       0
##  7 Chapter 1                                                      7       1
##  8 ""                                                             8       1
##  9 ""                                                             9       1
## 10 It is a truth universally acknowledged, that a singl~         10       1
## 11 of a good fortune, must be in want of a wife.                 11       1
\end{verbatim}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  How can we make this text into a format we can work with?
\end{itemize}

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[fragile]{Tokenizing}
\protect\hypertarget{tokenizing}{}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  A \textbf{token} is a meanginful unit of text. For us, that will be a
  single word
\item
  Tokenizing is simply splitting a body of text into tokens, which can
  achieved using the function \texttt{unnest\_tokens()}
\end{itemize}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{tidy_pp <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{pp }\OperatorTok{%>%}
\StringTok{  }\KeywordTok{unnest_tokens}\NormalTok{(word, text)}
\NormalTok{tidy_pp}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## # A tibble: 122,204 x 3
##    linenumber chapter word     
##         <int>   <int> <chr>    
##  1          1       0 pride    
##  2          1       0 and      
##  3          1       0 prejudice
##  4          3       0 by       
##  5          3       0 jane     
##  6          3       0 austen   
##  7          7       1 chapter  
##  8          7       1 1        
##  9         10       1 it       
## 10         10       1 is       
## # ... with 122,194 more rows
\end{verbatim}

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[fragile]{Tokenizing cont.}
\protect\hypertarget{tokenizing-cont.}{}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  With the \texttt{unnest\_tokens()} function, we can easily format any
  body of text into a user-friendly data frame
\item
  First argument: name of column/variable that text is being unnested
  into
\item
  Second argument: name of column/variable that is to be unnested
\item
  Other details:

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    All other columns kept
  \item
    Punctuation removed
  \item
    Defaults is to convert tokens to lowercase
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\end{frame}

\hypertarget{sentiment-analysis}{%
\section{Sentiment analysis}\label{sentiment-analysis}}

\begin{frame}{Sentiment lexicons}
\protect\hypertarget{sentiment-lexicons}{}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Now that we have looked at a per-word/token level, we may be
  interested in determining the general emotion of the text/author
\item
  We can consider a word to have a particular emotion attached to it
\item
  We can consider a piece of text as a combination of its individual
  words, so the sentiment of an entire text is the sum of the sentiments
  of its individual words
\item
  There are three general-purpose sentiment lexicons: AFINN, bing, and
  nrc
\end{itemize}

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[fragile]{AFINN}
\protect\hypertarget{afinn}{}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  AFINN assigns each word an integer score between -5 and 5
\item
  Negative scores indicate negative sentiment, and positive scores
  indicate the opposite
\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
## # A tibble: 2,477 x 2
##    word       value
##    <chr>      <dbl>
##  1 abandon       -2
##  2 abandoned     -2
##  3 abandons      -2
##  4 abducted      -2
##  5 abduction     -2
##  6 abductions    -2
##  7 abhor         -3
##  8 abhorred      -3
##  9 abhorrent     -3
## 10 abhors        -3
## # ... with 2,467 more rows
\end{verbatim}

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[fragile]{bing}
\protect\hypertarget{bing}{}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  The bing lexicon categorizes words into one of two categories:
  `positive' or `negative'
\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
## # A tibble: 6,786 x 2
##    word        sentiment

##  1 2-faces     negative

##  6 abominate   negative 
##  7 abomination negative 
##  8 abort       negative 
##  9 aborted     negative 
## 10 aborts      negative 
## # ... with 6,776 more rows
\end{verbatim}

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[fragile]{Important notes about sentiment lexicons}
\protect\hypertarget{important-notes-about-sentiment-lexicons}{}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Not every English word is in a lexicon
\end{itemize}

\begin{verbatim}
## # A tibble: 0 x 2
## # ... with 2 variables: word <chr>, sentiment <chr>
\end{verbatim}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  These lexicons do not account for qualifiers before a word (ex. ``not
  happy'') because these lexicons are constructed for one-word tokens
  only
\item
  If we sum up each word's sentiment, it is possible for a piece of text
  to average out to a sentiment of zero/neutral
\end{itemize}

\end{frame}

\hypertarget{comparing-candidates}{%
\section{Comparing candidates}\label{comparing-candidates}}

\begin{frame}{Plot of word frequency}
\protect\hypertarget{plot-of-word-frequency}{}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  We can visualize the differences and similarities in word frequencies
  between two candidates:
  \includegraphics{textanalysis_slides_files/figure-beamer/frequency-plot-1.pdf}
\item
  Words near the blue line are used with roughly equal frequencies
  between Joe Biden and Elizabeth Warren
\item
  Words far away from the blue line are favored much more by one
  candidate than the other
\end{itemize}

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{tf-idf}
\protect\hypertarget{tf-idf}{}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  How to quantify what a document is about?

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Term frequency (tf): how often a word occurs

    \begin{itemize}
    \tightlist
    \item
      Not always the best measurement due to common words like ``the'',
      ``and'', etc. List of stop words is not sustainable
    \end{itemize}
  \item
    Inverse document frequency (idf): increases weight of rare words and
    decreases weight of common words in a document
    \[idf(\text{word}) = \ln \left(\dfrac{\text{number of documents}}{\text{number of documents containing word}} \right)\]
  \end{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{tf-idf} is the prodct of tf and idf, and is intended to
  measure how important a word is relative to the document it came from
\end{itemize}

\end{frame}

\item

  number of words used by that candidate (term frequency)

  The plots for the candidates look quite similar, with many words that

\begin{frame}{Log-odds ratio}
\protect\hypertarget{log-odds-ratio}{}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Looking beyond raw frequencies, we can now begin to investigate which
  candidate is more likely to use a given word in a tweet
\item
  To do so, we will utilize the \textbf{log-odds ratio}
  \[\text{OR}_{A:B} = \dfrac{\text{odds}_A}{\text{odds}_B} = \dfrac{\text{prob}(word)_A}{\text{prob}(word)_B}\]
  \begin{align*}
  \log \text{OR}_{A:B} = \log \left( \dfrac{\text{prob}(word)_A}{\text{prob}(word)_B}\right) &= \log \left( \dfrac{n_A / total_A}{n_B / total_B}\right) \\ 
  & \approx \log \left( \dfrac{(n+1)_A / (total+1)_A}{(n+1)_B / (total+1)_B}\right)
  \end{align*}
\item
  Equal odds corresponds to OR = 1, which corresponds to log(OR) = 0
\end{itemize}

\end{frame}
